import java.util.HashSet;

public int numDupDigitsAtMostN(int n) {
    int count = 0;
    for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        HashSet<Integer> digits = new HashSet<>();
        int num = i;
        while (num != 0) {
            int digit = num % 10;
            if (digits.contains(digit)) {
                count++;
                break;
            } else {
                digits.add(digit);
            }
            num /= 10;
        }
    }
    return count;
}
```

    The algorithm iterates over the range of numbers from 1 to n inclusive. For each number, it extracts the digits by taking the remainder when dividing by 10 (`num % 10`) and adds it to a set (or hash set in Java) of digits. If a digit is already present in the set, it means that the digit is repeated, so we increment the count and break this iteration. At the end, we return the count of numbers with at least one repeated digit.
